The `json.put()` function just adds the `LocalDateTime` object to the `HashMap` of the JSON object. It will not perform any formatting to your `LocalDateTime` object. And when you call `toString()`, the date object will also use `toString()`. The library that you are using is very useful and customizable, but [Jackson][1] can provide you with different formats and customizations.

Secondly, the format that you want to use (an array) is a very weird format that is not recommended. If you really want to do that, then create a function that does that for you:

```java
public int[] dateToArray(LocalDateTime localDateTime)
{
    int year = localDateTime.getYear();
    int month = localDateTime.getMonthValue();
    int day = localDateTime.getDayOfMonth();
    int h = localDateTime.getHour();
    int m = localDateTime.getMinute();
    int s = localDateTime.getSecond();
    int sx = localDateTime.getNano();

    return new int[]{year, month, day, h, m, s, sx};
}
```


  [1]: https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson

